cs.NI, cs.LG, cs.IT, cs.SY, cs.DC 

This paper is likely to belong to the cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) category as it deals with the design of a MAC protocol for WLANs. The use of learning algorithms suggests that it could also belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) category. The paper also deals with information theory and scheduling, which could place it in the cs.IT (Information Theory) category. The design of a fair access scheme suggests that it could belong to the cs.SY (Systems and Control) category. Finally, the decentralised nature of the proposed MAC protocol could place it in the cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) category.
